Activity 1: Starting Small

Your team has chosen to use the Mistral 7B Large Language Model for the project. This model needs about 16 GB of GPU memory to run well for basic tasks. However, for the best performance, especially with bigger tasks, more memory is helpful. If the team plans to train or fine-tune the model, they might need around 32 GB or more.

The team has asked for a server with NVIDIA L40S GPUs. The NVIDIA L40S has 48 GB of GPU memory, which is more than enough to smoothly run the Mistral 7B model. The extra memory will ensure that the model works well for both basic tasks and more complex tasks such as retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) and fine-tuning. Therefore, the L40S is a great choice for the team's needs now and in the future. To host these GPUs, you have selected the Cisco UCS C240 M7 Rack Server.

Content Review Question

Incorrect

Initially, you wanted to connect the server with the NVIDIA L40S GPU to the HPC data center. However, the HPC team told you that this approach is not allowed.

Which of the following available connections is the best solution to connect the server?

Answer

The correct answer is Connect the server to 10G Catalyst ports. The 10G Catalyst ports offer the best possible bandwidth out of the options available. These ports should hopefully handle the high data transfer rates that are required by the NVIDIA L40S GPU and the Mistral 7B model, ensuring performance for the project.

The answer Connect the server to 1G Catalyst ports is incorrect. The 1G Catalyst ports do not provide sufficient bandwidth for the high-performance requirements of the NVIDIA L40S GPU and the Mistral 7B model, which would benefit from higher-speed connections. You have a better option, option B, which offers 10G connectivity.

The answer Connect the server to a local office router is incorrect. A local office router typically lacks the required bandwidth and performance capabilities that are needed for high-performance computing tasks. So, it is an unsuitable choice for connecting the server.

The answer Connect the server to the data center switches in the HPC environment is incorrect. The HPC team has specifically told you that you are not allowed to connect the server to the data center switches in the HPC environment.

Users have been noticing that the LLM application is not performing as expected. The processing times are long but at the same time there is underutilization of the GPU capabilities. This issue arises because the NVIDIA L40S GPU, which is quite a capable graphical card, recommends a minimum of a 2x25Gbps Network Interface Card (NIC) to function optimally. However, the current connection (as you might remember from the previous question) is only through a 2x10Gbps link, which is insufficient.

The good news is that the C240M7 server is equipped with a Cisco VIC 15427, which has four 10/25/50Gbps ports. Unfortunately, the small rack where the server is located only has Catalyst switches with 10Gbps ports. You have identified a solution to connect to 25Gbps server ports in a small rack that is located in a neighboring room, which is 20 meters (approximately 66 feet) away.

Content Review Question

Incorrect

Which type of connection should you make to connect the 2x25Gbps ports from the server VIC to the Catalyst switch?

Answer

The correct answer is Use a 25Gbps fiber optic cable with SFP-25G-SR transceivers. A 25Gbps fiber optic cable with SFP-25G-SR transceivers can handle the 20-meter distance and provide the necessary bandwidth for optimal performance of the NVIDIA L40S GPU.

The answer Use a 10Gbps Ethernet cable with SFP-10G-SR transceivers is incorrect. A 10Gbps Ethernet cable with SFP-10G-SR transceivers will not provide the necessary bandwidth for the NVIDIA L40S GPU. This option maintains the current bandwidth, which is insufficient.

The answer Use a 25Gbps DAC (Direct Attach Copper) cable is incorrect. While a DAC cable (also known as Twinax cable) can support 25Gbps, it is generally used for shorter distances (up to 10 meters). The 20-meter distance exceeds this limit.

The answer Use a 25Gbps fiber optic cable with SFP-25G-ER transceivers is incorrect. Although a 25Gbps fiber optic cable with SFP-25G-ER transceivers can support very long distances (up to 40 kilometers), this option is unnecessary for the 20-meter distance. Also, it would be incredibly costly.

Keep going!
